<?xml version="1.0" encoding="UTF-8"?>
<task id="R7-033" project="spaarke-ai-platform-unification-r7">
  <metadata>
    <title>Implement BFF endpoint GET /api/ai/playbook-builder/executor-config-schemas</title>
    <status>not-started</status>
    <wave>3</wave>
    <estimated-effort>2-3 hours</estimated-effort>
    <tags>bff-api, code-impl, wave-3</tags>
    <rigor-level>FULL</rigor-level>
    <parallel-safe>true</parallel-safe>
    <dependencies>032</dependencies>
    <fr-coverage>FR-16 (endpoint portion)</fr-coverage>
  </metadata>

  <prompt>
    With every executor declaring a schema (task 032), expose them via a BFF endpoint. Per FR-16 the
    working URL is `GET /api/ai/playbook-builder/executor-config-schemas`. The endpoint is a thin
    facade over the executor registry — it iterates `INodeExecutor` implementations, calls
    `GetConfigSchema()` on each, and returns a dictionary keyed by the executor's enum integer.
    PlaybookBuilder canvas (Wave 8 task 083) consumes this endpoint.
  </prompt>

  <role>
    Senior .NET backend developer. Follow the existing PlaybookBuilder endpoint pattern. Minimal handler,
    inject the executor registry (or enumerate `IEnumerable&lt;INodeExecutor&gt;`), return a
    `Dictionary&lt;int, ExecutorConfigSchema&gt;` payload. AuthN required.
  </role>

  <goal>
    1. New endpoint route `GET /api/ai/playbook-builder/executor-config-schemas` registered in BFF
    2. Handler returns `200 OK` with `Dictionary&lt;int, ExecutorConfigSchema&gt;` keyed by `ExecutorType` integer (post-Wave-2 enum)
    3. Endpoint requires authentication (uses the same auth policy as sibling PlaybookBuilder endpoints)
    4. Endpoint is thin — no DTO transformation beyond the schema records themselves
    5. Build passes; manual smoke (cURL or browser) returns valid JSON
  </goal>

  <inputs>
    <file purpose="design-doc">projects/spaarke-ai-platform-unification-r7/notes/spikes/getconfigschema-design.md</file>
    <file purpose="design-spec">projects/spaarke-ai-platform-unification-r7/spec.md</file>
    <file purpose="project-claude">projects/spaarke-ai-platform-unification-r7/CLAUDE.md</file>
    <file purpose="program">src/server/api/Sprk.Bff.Api/Program.cs</file>
    <file purpose="existing-playbook-builder-endpoints">src/server/api/Sprk.Bff.Api/Api/Ai/ — find existing PlaybookBuilder endpoints to mirror</file>
    <file purpose="interface">src/server/api/Sprk.Bff.Api/Services/Ai/Nodes/INodeExecutor.cs</file>
    <file purpose="executor-registry">src/server/api/Sprk.Bff.Api/Services/Ai/Nodes/NodeExecutorRegistry.cs</file>
    <file purpose="bff-constraints">.claude/constraints/bff-extensions.md</file>
  </inputs>

  <constraints>
    <constraint source="ADR-010">DI Minimalism — endpoint handler is a static method; injects `IEnumerable&lt;INodeExecutor&gt;` (DI built-in) or existing `INodeExecutorRegistry` if registry exposes enumeration.</constraint>
    <constraint source="ADR-013">BFF AI Architecture — thin facade endpoint, no new dispatch surface.</constraint>
    <constraint source="ADR-029">BFF Publish Hygiene — verify publish-size delta at task 036.</constraint>
    <constraint source="ADR-038">Testing Strategy — endpoint integration test in task 034 mocks `IOpenAiClient` only (executors are real). No banned `Mock&lt;HttpMessageHandler&gt;` or DI-registration tests.</constraint>
    <constraint source="CLAUDE.md §11">Component justification triple:
      1. Existing: no endpoint serves typed schemas today; PlaybookBuilder canvas hand-edits sprk_configjson.
      2. Extension: the endpoint is added to the existing PlaybookBuilder endpoint family — not a new endpoint family.
      3. Cost-of-doing-nothing: Wave 8 task 083 (typed form renderer) cannot ship; FR-23 acceptance criterion blocked.
    </constraint>
    <constraint source="bff-extensions.md">Pre-merge checklist applies. Placement decision: keep IN BFF — canvas-facing endpoint, lightweight, no AI internals leakage. Document in commit.</constraint>
    <constraint source="bff-extensions.md §F.1">No conditional DI registration; endpoint maps unconditionally. No Null-Object kill-switch needed.</constraint>
    <constraint source="DO NOT CHANGE">Use the URL `GET /api/ai/playbook-builder/executor-config-schemas` per spec FR-16. If a sibling PlaybookBuilder endpoint convention strongly suggests a different shape (e.g., camelCase vs kebab-case), FOLLOW the sibling convention but DOCUMENT the divergence in the commit message and design doc as an Open Question for sign-off.</constraint>
    <constraint source="AUTH">Endpoint requires authenticated user (same policy as sibling PlaybookBuilder endpoints). Do NOT make it anonymous.</constraint>
  </constraints>

  <knowledge>
    <topic>ai/node-executor-authoring</topic>
    <files>
      <file>.claude/patterns/ai/node-executor-authoring.md</file>
      <file>.claude/constraints/bff-extensions.md</file>
      <file>docs/adr/ADR-010-di-minimalism.md</file>
      <file>docs/adr/ADR-013-bff-ai-architecture.md</file>
      <file>docs/adr/ADR-029-bff-publish-hygiene.md</file>
      <file>docs/adr/ADR-038-testing-strategy.md</file>
      <file>src/server/api/Sprk.Bff.Api/CLAUDE.md</file>
    </files>
    <patterns>
      <pattern name="existing PlaybookBuilder endpoints" location="src/server/api/Sprk.Bff.Api/Api/Ai/">
        Mirror route prefix, auth policy, and response style.
      </pattern>
      <pattern name="INodeExecutorRegistry" location="src/server/api/Sprk.Bff.Api/Services/Ai/Nodes/NodeExecutorRegistry.cs">
        If the registry exposes enumeration of registered executors, prefer that over raw `IEnumerable&lt;INodeExecutor&gt;` injection.
      </pattern>
    </patterns>
  </knowledge>

  <context>
    <background>
      The endpoint is the contract surface between BFF and PlaybookBuilder canvas. Wave 8 task 083
      hits this URL on canvas load (or per-executor on selection) and uses the response to drive
      typed form rendering. Schema is static per BFF instance — could cache; spec does NOT require
      caching in v1 (in-memory is fine, regenerated per request is fine — 33 executors × shallow
      schemas is negligible compute).
    </background>
    <dependencies>
      <dependency task="032" status="not-started-but-required">All 33 executors return a schema (rich or Empty).</dependency>
    </dependencies>
    <related-work>
      <item>Task 034 adds xUnit tests for this endpoint.</item>
      <item>Task 035 documents the schema shape in `docs/architecture/AI-ARCHITECTURE.md`.</item>
      <item>Task 083 (Wave 8) is the canvas-side consumer.</item>
    </related-work>
  </context>

  <steps>
    <step order="0" name="Rigor Declaration">
      Output: 🔒 RIGOR LEVEL: FULL · 📋 REASON: code-impl in BFF (new endpoint, .cs file modification, tag bff-api, ADR-010+013+029+038 applicable) — quality gates Step 9.5 required · Proceeding with Step 0...
    </step>
    <step order="1" name="Load context">
      Read project CLAUDE.md + spec.md FR-16 + plan.md Wave 3 + task 030 design doc + `.claude/constraints/bff-extensions.md`.
    </step>
    <step order="2" name="Verify dependency">
      Confirm task 032 shipped: all 33 executors have GetConfigSchema().
    </step>
    <step order="3" name="Find existing PlaybookBuilder endpoint location">
      Use Grep to find existing routes prefixed with `/api/ai/playbook-builder/`. Identify the file they live in (likely `Api/Ai/PlaybookBuilderEndpoints.cs` or similar). Mirror auth policy + style.
    </step>
    <step order="4" name="Decide handler source for executors">
      If `INodeExecutorRegistry` exposes `IEnumerable&lt;INodeExecutor&gt; GetAll()` (or similar), inject the registry. Otherwise inject `IEnumerable&lt;INodeExecutor&gt;` — the DI container provides all Singleton registrations.
    </step>
    <step order="5" name="Implement the endpoint">
      Register the route. Sketch:
      <![CDATA[
      app.MapGet("/api/ai/playbook-builder/executor-config-schemas",
          (IEnumerable<INodeExecutor> executors) =>
          {
              var registry = new Dictionary<int, ExecutorConfigSchema>();
              foreach (var executor in executors)
              {
                  foreach (var type in executor.SupportedActionTypes)
                  {
                      registry[(int)type] = executor.GetConfigSchema();
                  }
              }
              return Results.Ok(registry);
          })
          .RequireAuthorization();
      ]]>
      (Adapt to existing PlaybookBuilder endpoint style — extract to a typed handler if convention requires.)
    </step>
    <step order="6" name="Build">
      Run: dotnet build src/server/api/Sprk.Bff.Api/
      Goal: 0 errors, 0 NEW warnings.
    </step>
    <step order="7" name="Run existing tests">
      Run: dotnet test (focus on Sprk.Bff.Api.Tests). Goal: no regression. Endpoint-specific tests land in task 034.
    </step>
    <step order="8" name="Manual smoke (optional but recommended)">
      Run the BFF locally; hit the endpoint with a valid auth token; verify JSON payload includes all 33 executor types as integer keys and the 5 priority schemas have populated `fields`.
    </step>
    <step order="9" name="Verify acceptance">
      Open the endpoint file in editor; confirm all goal bullets satisfied (URL, auth, return shape, no DTO transformation).
    </step>
    <step order="9.5" name="Quality gates (FULL rigor)">
      Run `/code-review` on changes. Run `/adr-check` against ADR-010 + ADR-013 + ADR-029 + ADR-038 + bff-extensions.md.
      Fix any findings before commit.
    </step>
    <step order="10" name="Update current-task.md + TASK-INDEX">
      Mark task 033 status complete; advance current-task.md to task 034.
    </step>
    <step order="11" name="Commit">
      Commit endpoint file (+ any Program.cs changes if registration there) with conventional message.
      Example: feat(bff/r7): expose GET executor-config-schemas endpoint (Wave 3 task 033, FR-16)
    </step>
  </steps>

